review_text:
Probably,Elephant falls is the most beautiful & popular place with in Shillong.

Must visit during rainy season. As you will be able to see three step waterfalls in its complete form. Dont visit during winter.

Elephant falls is quite close to Shillong. It has 3 falls. There are around 50 steps to get to the bottom. The hike down can be a little taxing but it is well worth it. Its not that difficult for aged persons also.

You have to pay 100 rs for each as entry fee for this site.Free parking is available.

There are some shops selling local handicrafts. Clean washrooms are available. Some small restaurants are also available.

There is a place where one can get tribal costumes on rent. They will even dress you up with all accessories.

The place is pretty clean and nicely maintained. Waterfall has good amount of flow and water looks pristine clean.

Elephant Falls,Shillong is the epitome of the word picturesque. Chunk of heaven on Earth

review_text: The falls is originally called only as three slide falls because it makes three cascade from the top to bottom. The top slide is at the entrance few steps below and second one in between and third and final one at the bottom. A total of 180 steps exactly to go down the falls. Why the name elephant falls is because the rock at the bottom most of the cascade looked like an elephant hence the British named it as Elephant falls and hence the name is from them. The people at the falls whether it is a contractor or the employees of government, they take extreme care in the upkeep of the falls meticulously clean. There are two caves type formation en-route which is a good place for taking selfies and pictures. Fortunately no bathing is allowed due to which the falls are clean. Not a great roaring falls but at the same time calm and serene falls to fulfill your hearts desire. The parking place is great to occupy at least 100 vehicles.

review_text: It is one of the best multi-tier waterfall in India. The original local name for the falls is Ka Kshaid Lai Pateng Khohsiew, which translates to the three - step waterfall. This rock was destroyed in the 1897 due to an earthquake A ticket costing 20 INR is required to view the fall

It is in the east Khasi hills- Mylliem.
A mountain spring descends through 2 tiers of waterfalls. It is named after an elephant shaped rock discovered here, which was later destroyed by the 1897 earthquake.
One must descend down the steps to the lowest level to capture the beautiful waterfall in photographs.
Tourists can get pictures in traditional Khasi costumes here.
One can buy local handicrafts here too.

review_text: A beautiful place with some marvellous falls in Shillong. Must visit during rainy season. But dont visit in December to February. If it is raining when you visit, do not worry at all. The shopkeepers will rent you colourful umbrellas just for Rs. 20. There are some shops that sell some local handicrafts. Bargaining is common. Clean washrooms are available. Some restaurants cater tea and Maggie. No vegetarian restaurant can be found. There is a place where one can get tribal costumes on rent. They will even dress you up with all accessories. However, they do not have cameras. You have to click with your own camera or mobile phones.

This is a popular waterfall that is open to public at an entry fee of Rs. 100 per person. The place can be quickly covered within 45 mins to an hour. Since there are stairs it can be covered easily.

The place is pretty clean and nicely maintained. Waterfall has good amount of flow and water looks pristine clean. They have put a ropeline beyond which you are not allowed to pics.

You will find stalls for snacks and refreshment and also some selling handicraft items.

This place draws a lot of people and is a good place to visit for a quick explore.

review_text: This place is located about 25 km from Shillong city and has three water falls located at different levels. There are a few stalls selling local handicraft products and refreshments, in close vicinity. Also theres a children play area with 3-4 slides. The place also has a studio to click photographs, dressed in the traditional attire. The place can be easily covered in around 1 hour. Entry fee payable is Rs 100 per person.

name: Niran kumar Nath
review_text: Beautiful place. Originally the Khasi people named this fall Ka Kshaid lai pateng khohsiew (three steps water falls) because the water falls into three steps. When the British people came and found the water falls they named it Elephant Falls because on the left side of the falls their was a rock resembled the Elephant but this rock was destroyed by the earthquake in the year 1897.

It is a two-tier waterfall in this beautiful state of India.
This place is named as Elephant falls as it used to have the elephant-shaped rock on one side of the fall which disintegrated and was washed away due to an earthquake.
Nice place to enjoy mesmerizing sound of the fountain, to get some decent photos.
Boating service was available there.

review_text:
The Elephant falls is s 3-step waterfalls near Shillong, Meghalaya in North Eastern India. It was named Elephant falls as there was once a huge rock shaped like an elephant near the falls. However, the was destroyed in the massive earthquake of 1897.
The falls is picturesque. The first step is almost st the road level, but the other two, especially the 3rd one, require to climb down about 140 steps. There is a small plunge pool below, where one can do watersports like boating etc.
It is easily approachable from Shillong.
There are a number of shops at the first level selling local handicrafts and eatables.

name: Amaresh Panda
review_text:
The original Khasi name for the falls is Ka Kshaid Lai Pateng Khohsiew, which translates to the three - step waterfall.This name is still used locally. However the modern name is explained by a signboard near the waterfall.The name originated in the British era when the Englishmen spotted a giant rock that looked like an elephant near the fall. This rock was destroyed in the 1897 due to an earthquake.
The first fall of Elephant Falls is an example of a horsetail-punchbowl waterfall. The first fall is very broad and is hidden among the trees. The second fall however, is quite domesticated and in the winters (and drier months) looks inconsequential. The third fall is the tallest and comes to view suddenly and looks most spectacular with crystal clear water falling over sharp rocks of myriad shapes.The sides of the waterfall are flanked by lush greenery and are rich in ferns.

name: Chindu Mathew
review_text:
Elephant Waterfalls is a superb place for relaxing with nature.
Elephant Waterfalls can be visited all year round. The months right after the monsoon are the best as the water flows with full might and the scenery created is one to remember for a long time.
Be careful a trip to these falls requires walking down a large flight of stairs (around 100 stairs). Hence, it is not recommended for the seniors who have a little difficulty in walking.
Also,the stairs might be slippery. So, make sure to wear comfortable footwear with a good grip
There are a few small shops selling cheap souvenirs and eating joints near the parking lot.
Timings is from 10 am to 6 pm. Photography is allowed here.
Overall, Elephant Falls is a great stopover destination before one head for further journeys into Meghalaya.

review_text:
Located near Shillong in Meghalaya is another great attraction called the Elephant falls. This waterfall is formed by combining three beautiful and alluring rivers. The name Elephant falls was initially a British name. The local Khasi referred to it as Ka Kshaid Lai Pateng Khohsiew which also means the three step waterfalls. But the British renamed this to Elephant falls because they spotted a rock that looked like an elephant.

The rock however doesn't exist anymore because the rock got destroyed in an earthquake. It is not really a task to reach the Elephant waterfalls with so many public transport options available. One of the most stunning and beautiful natural wonders of the North East, if you love anything scenic you should be here. Located very close to the Shillong peak, the Elephant falls should definitely be on your must visit list.

name: AK TIWARI Income Tax
review_text:
The Elephant Falls are a two-tier waterfall in Shillong, Meghalaya, India.The mountain stream descends through two successive falls set in dells of fern-covered rocks.
History
The original Khasi name for the falls is Ka Kshaid Lai Pateng Khohsiew, which translates to the three - step waterfall. This name is still used locally. However the modern name is explained by a signboard near the waterfall.The name originated in the British era when the Englishmen spotted a giant rock that looked like an elephant near the fall. This rock was destroyed in the 1987 due to an earthquake.

name: Hemanta Thoudam
review_text:
The name Elephant Falls was given by British officers who discovered its existence in the heart of the mountainous jungles of the Meghalaya. There was a curious rock on one side of the falls which eerily resembled an elephant and hence the nomenclature. The eponymous rock was however destroyed in an earthquake in the year 1897 and the residual rock has been disintegrated since then due to the continuous barrage of water falling from a high altitude.
Like everything else it was renamed by the British, the Elephant Falls had a name before it received a colonial makeover. In the local Khasi language, the name of the waterfall is Ka Kshaid Lai Pateng Khohshiew whose literal translation from the Khasi language means 'the three-step waterfall'. True to its name, the waterfall is divided into three steps literally. The first step of the waterfall is broad and sluggish and is lost amongst the dense forests all around, the second step though more concentrated lacks the huge drop and is often hidden from the public eye.

The third and the most important step comprises of a sheer vertical drop and a cascading flow of water which makes the falls one of the best waterfalls in the country. We can enjoy the beauty of two of the falls.

One can go to the Elephant Falls all year round but should really avoid the monsoon season due to the area becoming wet and prone to occasional landslides which would hamper the safety of tourists during that season. The summer season is a great time as one can beat the heat wave running throughout the country and enjoy a few days in the heart of nature.
Shillong Lovely place to enjoy Natures Beauty.
And Dont forget to visit world wettest place Mawsinram and enjoy Living Root Bridge.

name: Ritesh Kanu
review_text:
Its one of the most picturesque waterfalls in India.

The first of the three waterfalls are tucked between the dense trees and are very broad. The second waterfall reduces to thin strands of water and is almost negligible in winters due to the receding water levels.

The third and the most visible waterfall is the tallest with clear water flowing like a sheet of milk on the dark rocks in the backdrop.

Out of the three, the third waterfall tends to strike the visitors as the most impressive. Elephant Falls is a great stopover destination before one head for further journeys into Meghalaya.
